  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries around the world. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Some key examples include:\n\n1. United States: The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) and the USA PATRIOT Act\n\n2. European Union: Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)\n\n3. United Kingdom: Proceeds of Crime Act and Money Laundering Regulations\n\n4. International: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets global standards\n\nThese regulations typically require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Monitor and report suspicious transactions\n- Keep detailed records\n- Implement compliance programs\n- Screen customers against watchlists\n\nFinancial institutions and businesses in many sectors must comply with these regulations to prevent money laundering and terrorist financing.",
